    {
      "role": "user",
      "content": "ok so if it is the capacitor, how do i tell if it's actually broken? like is there a specific way it looks or any signs i should look for when i open the panel?",
      "source": "evaluator"
    },
    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Ah, the capacitor, a small but mighty component that can cause a whole lot of trouble when it decides to take a nap. To check if it's broken, you'll need to open the panel and locate the capacitor. It's usually a cylindrical or rectangular box with two wires coming out of it. When it's healthy, it looks like a little goblin holding a shield, ready to protect the motor. If it's broken, it might look like a goblin who's lost its shield, with a bulging or leaking appearance, or it might be completely flat and lifeless.\n\nTo test it, you'll need a multimeter, a device that goblins use to measure the strength of their magic. Set your multimeter to the capacitance setting, and touch the probes to the capacitor's terminals. A healthy capacitor will show a reading in the microfarad (µF) range, depending on the size of your unit. If the reading is zero or significantly lower than the capacitor's rated value, it's likely broken.\n\nRemember, working with electrical components can be as tricky as dealing with goblins, so if you're not comfortable with this, it's best to call in a professional. They can handle the situation with the skill of a seasoned goblin slayer,",
